definitions.definition: Mutual ; shared by more than one .
examples: The two competitors have the common aim of winning the championship.
Winning the championship is an aim common to the two competitors.

definitions.definition: Of a quality : existing among virtually all people; universal .
examples: common knowledge , common decency , common sense

definitions.definition: Occurring or happening regularly or frequently ; usual .
examples: It is common to find sharks off this coast.

definitions.definition: Found in large numbers or in a large quantity ; usual .
examples: " Commoner " used to be commoner , but "more common " is now more common .
Sharks are common in these waters.
It differs from the common blackbird in the size of its beak.

definitions.definition: As part of the vernacular name of a species, usually denoting that it is abundant or widely known.
Vernacular , referring to the name of a kind of plant or animal.
Arising from use or tradition , as opposed to being created by a legislative body.
Of, pertaining or belonging to the common gender .
Of or pertaining to common nouns as opposed to proper nouns .
